  "prompt": "Why does blue vitriol change its colour from blue to white on heating?",
  "response": "Blue vitriol, also known as copper sulfate pentahydrate (CuSO4\u00b75H2O), changes its color from blue to white upon heating due to the loss of water molecules. Let me explain the process in detail:\n\n1. Chemical composition:\n- Blue vitriol is a hydrated copper sulfate salt\n- It contains five water molecules (pentahydrate) in its crystal structure\n\n2. Heating process:\n- When heated, the water molecules are gradually removed from the crystal\n- This process is called dehydration\n- As water molecules are lost, the blue color transforms to white\n\n3. Chemical reaction:\nCuSO4\u00b75H2O (blue) \u2192 CuSO4 (white) + 5H2O (water)\n\n4. Reasons for color change:\n- The water molecules are responsible for the blue color\n- Without water, the anhydrous copper sulfate appears white\n- The crystal structure changes during dehydration\n\n5. Reversibility:\n- If water is added back to the white anhydrous copper sulfate, it will turn blue again\n\nThis color change is a characteristic property of copper sulfate pentahydrate and demonstrates the relationship between hydration and color in certain chemical compounds.",
